# FMAttack: Exploiting Authentication Gaps in the CXL Fabric Manager API for Data Destruction and Denial of Service

**M.N. Srivatsa Bharadwaj**
Samsung Semiconductor Research India (SSRI), Bengaluru, Karnataka, India

***

## Abstract
Compute Express Link (CXL) 4.0 defines a Fabric Manager (FM) API for orchestrating multi-tenant memory pools, dynamic capacity regions, and port-based routing across disaggregated CXL fabrics [1]. While the CXL Trusted Execution Environment Security Protocol (TSP) successfully utilizes hardware configuration locking and data sanitization to guarantee data confidentiality (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 11.5.4.8.1), the specification explicitly accepts Denial of Service (DoS) as out of scope [1]. Furthermore, the CXL specification allows SPDM session binding for FM commands to be optional (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 7.6.3), leaving the management transport exposed [1]. We identify five normative gaps in the CXL specification: the FM API command payload tables contain no authentication fields, SPDM session binding is not strictly mandated, and the software routing table maintained by the FM can diverge silently from the hardware routing table in the CXL switch [1]. Exploiting these gaps under an unauthenticated network attacker threat model, we construct four concrete attacks: VPPB-REBIND (ATK-1), PORTDOS (ATK-2), DCDRAIN (ATK-3), and TUNNELSPOOF (ATK-4). These attacks allow an unauthenticated attacker to permanently destroy multi-tenant data via hardware sanitization mechanisms and sever shared physical interconnects [1]. We propose four complementary hardware and software defenses—hardware-anchored ownership registers, SPDM + RATS attestation binding, orchestrator-signed command tokens, and per-tenant hardware isolation—to secure the control plane for CXL 5.0 [2].

**Index Terms**—CXL, Fabric Manager, FMAPI, MCTP, SPDM, multi-tenant, disaggregated memory, dynamic capacity device, denial of service.

