## I. INTRODUCTION
Compute Express Link (CXL) has emerged as the dominant interconnect standard for memory disaggregation in hyperscale data-centers. CXL 4.0 refined Dynamic Capacity Devices (DCD), Port-Based Routing (PBR), and the Fabric Manager (FM) API that orchestrates all of these components [1]. The FM API is the control plane for every multi-tenant CXL fabric, serving as the sole mechanism through which memory regions are allocated across tenants and virtual PCI-to-PCI bridges (vPPBs) are bound to logical devices (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 7.6.1) [1]. 

Recent additions to the CXL specification, specifically the CXL Trusted Execution Environment Security Protocol (TSP), have fortified the architecture against data theft by mandating SPDM authentication and `CONFIG_LOCKED` hardware states for confidential computing (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 11.5) [1]. However, this robust defense of *confidentiality* has created a blind spot regarding *availability*. The CXL security model explicitly states: "Denial of service attacks are beyond the scope of this specification" (CXL 4.0 Spec) [1]. 

Compounding this availability gap is the permissive language regarding management bus security. The CXL specification states that the FM API *may* be transported inside an SPDM session (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 7.6.3), making cryptographic transport security optional rather than mandatory [1]. We demonstrate that an unauthenticated network attacker on the Management Component Transport Protocol (MCTP) bus can weaponize CXL's own security features to permanently destroy multi-tenant data and expand blast radiuses across isolated physical heads.

We make the following contributions:
1.  We perform a systematic security audit of the CXL FM API command set and identify five normative specification gaps (GAP-1 through GAP-5) that leave FM command authentication undefined by the CXL standard [1], [2].
2.  We demonstrate that the MCTP transport used by the FM API allows any unauthenticated process on the network to issue FM commands directly to a CXL switch, bypassing the legitimate FM software entirely [2].
3.  We construct four end-to-end attacks (ATK-1 through ATK-4) that exploit these gaps to achieve unblockable denial-of-service, forced-removal data destruction, and command injection [1], [2].
4.  We propose a four-layer defense architecture and a concrete standardization roadmap to elevate FM authentication from an optional feature to a mandatory requirement [2].

