## II. BACKGROUND

### A. CXL Architecture and the Fabric Manager
CXL is a cache-coherent interconnect that supports pooled memory devices accessible by multiple hosts through a CXL fabric switch [1]. The Fabric Manager (FM) is defined as an "external logical process" responsible for configuring the CXL fabric (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 7.6.1) [1]. It communicates with CXL switches and devices using the FM API, a set of management commands transported over MCTP [1]. The FM API defines commands for physical port management (opcodes 0x5100–0x510F), vPPB management (opcodes 0x5200–0x520F), Multi-Logical Device (MLD) management (opcodes 0x5300–0x540F), DCD management (opcodes 0x5600–0x5607), and switch management (opcodes 0x5700–0x5716) (CXL 4.0 Spec, Table 8-397) [1].

### B. SPDM Authentication in CXL
CXL requires devices to support the Security Protocol and Data Model (SPDM) for device identity verification and secure session establishment [1]. However, the CXL specification language governing whether SPDM sessions *must* be used for FM API command transport is consistently permissive. Transport security is explicitly noted as optional, stating that commands "may be transported" via SPDM (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 7.6.3) [1].

### C. Dynamic Capacity Devices and Hardware Sanitization
A DCD exposes DC Regions from which the FM allocates extents to hosts using `Initiate Dynamic Capacity Add` and `Initiate Dynamic Capacity Release` commands (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 7.6.7.6) [1]. Under the TSP, when capacity is forcefully removed, the target hardware is mandated to automatically overwrite or cryptographically scramble the data before the capacity can be reassigned to prevent data leakage (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 8.2.10.9.9.4 and Table 7-73) [1].

