## V. ATTACK DESIGN

### A. ATK-1: vPPB-Rebind (Forced Unbind DoS)
**Objective:** Sever a victim tenant's connection and hijack the routing path [2].

**Mechanism:** CXL switches fundamentally prohibit the FM from tunneling CXL.io memory requests to any port that is actively bound to a host (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 7.2.3.1) [1]. To bypass this, the unauthenticated attacker issues an `Unbind vPPB` command (Opcode 0x5202, Table 7-36) over the MCTP bus [1]. Because SPDM is optional (GAP-2) and the payload lacks an HMAC (GAP-1), the switch blindly executes it [1], [2]. When unbound, the port becomes FM-owned, acting as a Surprise Removal (DoS) for the host. The FM software routing table now diverges from the hardware state (GAP-3) [2].

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker as Unauthenticated Attacker
    participant Switch as CXL Switch (Hardware)
    participant Victim as Victim Tenant
    Note over Attacker,Switch: No SPDM authentication required (GAP-1, GAP-2)
    Attacker->>Switch: UNBIND_VPPB (opcode 0x5202)
    Switch->>Victim: Detach physical binding (Surprise Removal DoS)
    Switch-->>Attacker: UNBIND_RESPONSE
    Attacker->>Switch: BIND_VPPB (opcode 0x5201) to attacker LD
    Switch->>Switch: Updates hardware routing table
    Note over Switch: Hardware routing table now diverges<br/>from FM software inventory (GAP-3)
```

### B. ATK-2: PortDoS (Architecturally Sanctioned DoS)
**Objective:** Disable a shared upstream switch port, severing connectivity for all tenants [2].

**Mechanism:** Exploiting the fact that physical port control requires no token (GAP-1), the unauthenticated attacker sends a `Set Physical Port State` command (Opcode 0x5101, Table 7-19) to disable the port [1], [2]. Because the specification explicitly accepts DoS as out of scope, the hardware complies, instantly taking down the multi-tenant topology [1].

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker as Unauthenticated Attacker
    participant Switch as CXL Switch
    participant Victims as All Tenants on Port
    Attacker->>Switch: GET_PHYSICAL_PORT_STATE (opcode 0x5100)
    Switch-->>Attacker: Port list + states
    Attacker->>Switch: SET_PHY_PORT_STATE (opcode 0x5101, DISABLED)
    Switch->>Victims: Port physically disabled
    Note over Victims: Massive Denial of Service
```

### C. ATK-3: DCDrain (Forced Removal Data Destruction)
**Objective:** Leverage hardware sanitization to instantly destroy a victim's active memory [2].

**Mechanism:** The attacker sends an `Initiate Dynamic Capacity Release` (Opcode 0x5605, Table 7-73) directly to the DCD device, bypassing the FM entirely (GAP-4) [1], [2]. The attacker sets the **Forced Removal** flag (Bit 4) to 1 [1]. Under the TSP, to prevent data leakage during a forced removal, the hardware automatically executes cryptographic scrambling or overwriting (Sanitize on Release) if Bit 5 is set or by default depending on the security policy [1]. The attacker thus leverages the device's own confidentiality mechanisms to permanently destroy the victim's data (e.g., an LLM KV-Cache) without the host OS receiving a warning interrupt [2].

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker as Unauthenticated Attacker
    participant DCD as DCD Device Hardware
    participant Victim as Victim Tenant Host
    Note over Attacker,DCD: Direct MCTP access bypasses FM (GAP-4)
    Attacker->>DCD: DCD_RELEASE_CAPACITY (opcode 0x5605) + Forced Removal Flag
    Note over DCD: Hardware triggers Sanitize on Release (TSP)
    DCD->>DCD: Cryptographically scrambles / overwrites victim data
    Note over Victim: Live LLM KV-cache memory permanently destroyed.<br/>No OS interrupt generated.
```

### D. ATK-4: TunnelSpoof (The LD Pool CCI Pivot)
**Objective:** Pivot from a single isolated physical Head to gain global management over all tenants on a Multi-Headed Device [2].

**Mechanism:** CXL 4.0 mandates that Multi-Headed Devices expose a global LD Pool CCI accessible via tunneling (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 2.5) [1]. The attacker issues the `Tunnel Management Command` (Opcode 0x5300, Table 7-39) setting the Target Type to 1h (LD Pool CCI) [1]. The outer switch strips the header and forwards the encapsulated command to the global LD Pool CCI without verifying the inner command's cryptographic authorization (GAP-5) [1], [2]. The attacker successfully pivots out of their isolated physical head to gain execution rights over logical devices assigned to other tenants [2].

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker as Unauthenticated Attacker
    participant OuterSwitch as Outer CXL Switch
    participant InnerDevice as Global LD Pool CCI (Target)
    Attacker->>OuterSwitch: TUNNEL_MANAGEMENT_COMMAND (opcode 0x5300, Target Type 1h)
    Note over OuterSwitch: Switch strips outer header.<br/>No cryptographic check on inner origin (GAP-5).
    OuterSwitch->>InnerDevice: Forwards encapsulated FM API command
    InnerDevice->>InnerDevice: Executes command (believes it is from FM)
    InnerDevice-->>OuterSwitch: Response
    OuterSwitch-->>Attacker: TUNNEL_RESPONSE
```

