## VI. EVALUATION

### A. Simulation Environment and Results
We implemented a Python-based CXL fabric simulator utilizing four modules: `FabricModel`, `MCTPBus`, `DCDModel`, and `AttackHarness` [2]. Each attack was executed for 1,000 Monte-Carlo trials with randomized victim tenant IDs and target ports [2]. 

Because the CXL specification inherently lacks mandatory payload authentication for these control-plane operations, all four attacks achieved a **100% success rate** in simulation [2]. While previous drafts of this research extrapolated specific sub-microsecond physical latencies over the SMBus, we note that actual execution times will vary heavily depending on the out-of-band physical transport layer utilized (e.g., I2C, I3C, or PCIe VDMs). Regardless of physical transport speed, the logical success of the attacks is guaranteed by the current normative rules of the specification.

### B. Limitations
Our proposed software and hardware defenses target control-plane operations (the FM API), which are decoupled from the high-speed CXL.mem data-plane coherency traffic (CXL 4.0 Spec, Section 9.20.1) [1]. However, the precise latency overhead introduced by cryptographic token verification and SPDM binding on these specific management operations remains unmeasured in silicon and is flagged as future work [2].

