## VII. DEFENSE MECHANISMS AND STANDARDIZATION ROADMAP

To address the lack of control-plane authentication without breaking CXL.mem coherency protocols, we propose a four-layer defense architecture targeting CXL 5.0 Engineering Change Requests (ECRs) [2].

**D1: Hardware-Anchored Ownership Registers (ECR-FM-SEC-03)**
Each vPPB and DCD extent must be backed by a hardware ownership register in the switch ASIC that records the authoritative FM's SPDM device identity [2]. The switch acts as a zero-trust enforcer, rejecting commands mutating vPPB bindings or extent states unless the identity matches, mitigating GAP-3 and GAP-4 [2].

**D2: Mandatory SPDM + RATS Session Binding (ECR-FM-SEC-02)**
The CXL specification must change the language in Section 7.6.1 from "may" to "shall" [1], [2]. Forcing all FM API commands to be encrypted and integrity-protected at the transport layer neutralizes the Dolev-Yao network attacker [2].

**D3: Orchestrator-Signed Command Tokens (ECR-FM-SEC-01)**
FM API payloads must include a mandatory `CommandToken` field (an HMAC-SHA-256 keyed by the SPDM session) over the command opcode, payload, and sequence number [2]. This directly patches GAP-1 and provides replay protection without altering the physical link layer [2].

**D4: Per-Tenant Tunnel Attestation (ECR-FM-SEC-04)**
CXL Tunnel Management Commands (Table 7-39) must be extended with a mandatory `TunnelOriginToken` field [1], [2]. This preserves legitimate tunneling functionality but forces the outer switch to cryptographically verify the inner command's origin before forwarding it to the target device, closing GAP-5 [2].

***

## VIII. CONCLUSION

While CXL 4.0 successfully guarantees data confidentiality via the Trusted Execution Environment Security Protocol (TSP) [1], its reliance on optional transport security leaves the management bus highly vulnerable [1], [2]. FMAttack demonstrates that an unauthenticated network attacker can bypass the Fabric Manager software entirely [2]. By exploiting documented specification gaps, an attacker can issue raw control-plane commands to forcefully unbind tenants, instantly destroy active memory via hardware sanitization, and pivot across isolated physical heads [2]. By implementing mandatory SPDM binding, orchestrator-signed payload tokens, and hardware-anchored ownership registers, the CXL Consortium can elevate multi-tenant availability to the same tier of protection as confidentiality [2].
